    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "<!-- Before reporting: search existing issues and check the FAQ. -->\r\n\r\n- `nvim --version`: v0.5.0-dev+1268-g02909d150\r\n- `vim -u DEFAULTS` (version: ) behaves differently? N/A\r\n- Operating system/version: CentOS 7\r\n- Terminal name/version: xfce4-terminal 0.8.7.4\r\n- `$TERM`: tmux-256color\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce using `nvim -u NORC`\r\n\r\nThese steps can be done in a REPL for a language of your choosing:\r\n1. Open Neovim and identify the unix domain socket (`v:servername`)\r\n2. From the REPL, open a new connection to the socket.\r\n3. Find the channel for the connection. If it's not obvious from `nvim_list_chans` on its own, from the REPL call `nvim_set_client_info` to set a unique name, and then in Neovim look for the channel with a client with that name.\r\n4. From Neovim, `:call rpcrequest(<channel>, \"blockme\")`\r\n5. From the REPL, read the message from the unix domain socket to identify the message id for the request.\r\n6. Send an `nvim_echo` command.\r\n7. Confirm that Neovim successfully received it by reading the response from the socket.\r\n8. Observe that no output appeared on screen.\r\n9. Send a response with the same message id.\r\n10. Observe that Neovim now unlocks and the message is echoed.\r\n\r\n### Actual behaviour\r\nNo output appeared until after `rpcrequest` returned.\r\n\r\n### Expected behaviour\r\nOutput should appear immediately after being echoed.\r\n\r\nNote: `nvim_eval` with `input(\"prompt\")` successfully displays the prompt during an `rpcrequest`.\r\n",
